@node "Examples" "Examples"
@next "Author"
@prev "Menu_Start"

 @{b}Examples@{ub}
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
 Here are some examples for tooltype settings:

 @{b}1. Trashcan@{ub}

    ICONNAME=Trash
    COMMAND=Delete "%s(%|.info)"
    ICONFILE=Sys:Trashcan
    ICONPOS=-1,-1

    This is not perfect, because the icon will not
    automatically disappear after deleting. Therefor you
    have to use another tool, which uses the OS function
    DeleteDiskObject() for deleting icons.

 @{b}2. Viewer@{ub}

    ICONNAME=View
    COMMAND=Sys:Utilities/Multiview "%s"
    ICONFILE=Sys:Utilities/Multiview
    ICONPOS=600,20
    DONOTWAIT

    After start you will see the Multiview icon in the
    right top corner. If you throw an icon onto it, you
    will see the contents of the file.         
@endnode

@node "Menu_Start" "Workbench Start"
@next "Examples"
@prev "Shell_Start"

 @{b}Workbench start@{ub}
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
 If @{i}AppIcon@{ui} starts from Workbench it looks for some
 tooltypes, to get the needed information. The tooltypes
 are:

    ICONNAME     The name the icon will have when put
                 on the workbench screen

    ICONPOS      A position like  xxx,yyy, where the icon
                 should appear. If this tooltype is not
                 present, the position of the original
                 icon will be used.

    ICONFILE     Name of the icon file (@{b}without .info@{ub}),
                 which will be used for the image appearing
                 on the workbench.

    COMMAND      Command string, which will be executed each
                 time and for each icon, that you drop on
                 the AppIcon. For placeholders see @{"Using" link "Using" 0}.

 It is recommended to put AppIcon into @{i}Sys:WBStartup@{ui} and to
 add the tooltype @{i}DONOTWAIT@{ui}.            
@endnode

@node "Shell_Start" "Shell Start"
@next "Menu_Start"
@prev "Using"

 @{b}Shell start@{ub}
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
 The shell start is near equivalent to the @{"workbench start" link "Menu_Start" 0}.
 Try

    @{i}AppIcon ?@{ui}

 to get the template

    @{i}ICONFILE/A,COMMAND/A,IP=ICONPOS/K,IN=ICONNAME/K@{ui}

 The meaning of the options are the same as the tooltype
 meanings. Use

    @{i}Run >NIL: AppIcon ... ..@{ui}.

 to start the program.       
@endnode

@node "Using" "Using"
@next "Shell_Start"
@prev "Installation"

 @{b}Using@{ub}
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
 After the installation and start using the Shell or
 Workbench you can use AppIcon.

 There are 2 thing you can do:

   · drag icons onto the AppIcon
   · click twice on the AppIcon


 If you drag icons on the AppIcon, the command string will
 be executed. If the string contains placeholders, they will
 be replaced by the filename or part of the filename. Valid
 placeholders are:

 Placeholder  | replaced by
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
    %s        | the whole filename with path
    %o        | the filename without path and extension
    %f        | the filename without path
    %x        | the extension
    %p        | the path
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ

 If you click twice on the AppIcon a window will appear with
 some information about the default icon position and the
 command string. You have two choice now:

   · closing the window. The AppIcon will remain on the
     workbench.
   · quit. The AppIcon will disappear and the program will
     quit.        
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"
@next "Using"
@prev "What_it_is"

 @{b}Installation@{ub}
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
 Installation is very easy.

 · Drag it simply into the drawer Sys:WBstartup.
 · Click once on the icon
 · Press @{i}<Amiga i>@{ui} to see the tooltypes.
 · Add the tooltypes as you want.
 · Save the changes.
 · Click twice on the icon. A new icon should appear
   on the workbench screen.

 To get more AppIcons simply copy the Icon using the
 workbench. The program is only 9 KByte big. For saving
 memmory use hardlinks and the command @{i}makelink@{ui} from
 Commodore.

 See @{"Examples" link "Examples" 0} for some application ideas.             
@endnode

@node "What_it_is" "What it is"
@next "Installation"
@prev "Main"

 @{b}AppIcon - What it is@{ub}
 ŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻŻ
 With Amiga OS 2.0 or higher you can drag icon around and
 drop them on other icons or windows. Icons you can drop
 icons on are called AppIcons. @{"My" link "Author" 0} tool AppIcon gives you
 the possibility, to create very easely an AppIcon and
 execute a program with the dropped icon as parameter.

 For that you can supply an icon name for the image you want
 to see as icon on the workbench, a command string with
 placeholders for the dropped files, a position for the icon
 and a name for the icon. This can be done via tooltypes or
 parameters when using the shell.

 The best way to use AppIcon is to copy it to Sys:WBStartup,
 edit the tooltypes to your need, add @{i}DONOTWAIT@{ui} an reboot.

 I am using the tool for dismounting envoy drives, for looking
 into files via Multiview and many datatypes, for deleting files
 with a nice trashcan icon, giving icons a new default tool and
 making icons for fake iiňo     
@endnode

